[2]
Date: 14 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Polio Eradication Website [edited]
<http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/Indonesiapolio13May2005.pdf>

Outbreak of polio in Indonesia - updated 13 May 2005
-----------------------------------------------
On 13 May 2005, 2 additional polio cases were reported in Indonesia,
bringing the total number of cases to 8. The new cases are in the same
district as the 1st case. Vaccine has been shipped to the provinces where
supplemental immunization activities are scheduled to take place at the end
of the month [May 2005] in response to this outbreak.
11 May 2005: Confirmed today are 6 additional "positive contact" cases,
from the same village as the index case, bringing the total number of
positive contact cases to 14. All positive contact cases are from the same
village as the index case. A "contact case" is the positive isolation of
wild poliovirus from stool samples collected from a healthy child. During a
polio outbreak, stool samples are frequently collected from healthy
children in and around an affected area. This helps to determine the extent
of the wild poliovirus circulation in the immediate environment.
10 May 2005: 8 positive contact cases were confirmed from the same village
as the index case. The 1st round of the mop-up immunization campaign in
West Java, Banten and Jakarta provinces will be conducted on 31 May-2 Jun
2005. The 2nd campaign will be held on 28 Jun-1 Jul 2005. Both campaigns
will aim to reach all of the provinces' 5.2 million children under the age
of 5 years.
On 5 May 2005, 3 additional polio cases were reported in Indonesia,
bringing the total number of cases to 4. 2 of the 3 cases are from the same
village as the index polio case, and the 3rd is from a neighboring village.
The cases are 2 boys and one girl, all previously un-immunized, who had
onset of paralysis on 2, 9 and 10 Apr 2005. An immunization response has
already been conducted around these cases.
On 2 May 2005, the global reference laboratory in Mumbai, India confirmed a
wild poliovirus type 1 isolate, from an acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) case
identified by the national surveillance system in Gin Jaya village,
Sukabumi District, West Java, Indonesia. The case, an 18-month-old child
who was previously un-immunized, had onset of paralysis on 12 Mar 2005.
The findings of the investigation suggest recent introduction of wild
poliovirus, as genetic analysis of the virus demonstrates that its origin
is in west Africa, similar to the viruses which caused the 2003/04
outbreak. Further analysis suggests the virus traveled to Indonesia through
Sudan, and is similar to recently isolated viruses in Saudi Arabia and Yemen.
--
