Date: 16 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters Alert [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/JAK54025.htm>

Indonesia polio outbreak nearly contained: officials
-----------------------------------------------
Indonesia has nearly contained its 1st polio outbreak in a decade because
of fast action in vaccinating children in affected areas and a willingness
to seek international help, health officials said on Monday [16 May 2005].
Indonesian officials have detected 8 polio-infected patients since
discovering the 1st case last month [April 2005] about 100 km (62 miles)
south of Jakarta. Several suspected cases are under investigation, and a
mass vaccination is set for 31 May [2005].
All the infected children live close to the 1st case in Girijaya village
near the West Java city of Sukabumi, although one patient suffering from
the virus was brought to a Jakarta hospital by relatives who were oblivious
to the outbreak.
"We acted quickly," said Muhammad Nadirin, head of epidemiology
surveillance at the health ministry. "In less than 72 hours after the 1st
case, we conducted an outbreak response immunization in 15 villages around
the original location."
He said 12 800 children under the age of 5 in the area have been immunized
against the disease, which can cause irreversible paralysis, deformation
and sometimes death.
Indonesia's response contrasts with an explosion of cases in Yemen, another
country beset by a revival of polio. The World Health Organization (WHO)
says Yemen's outbreak could cripple more than 100 children before it is
brought under control.
The twin outbreaks in Indonesia and Yemen raised fears that the virus was
spreading from Africa and the Middle East to Asia and dealt a setback to a
WHO campaign to stop global transmission of polio by year-end [2005].
Indonesia plans to vaccinate about 5.2 million children on 31 May [2005]
across the provinces of West Java, Banten and the city of Jakarta, which,
administratively, is an individual province. On 28 Jun [2005], the same
children get a 2nd round of vaccinations.
"There are only small pockets that have not received immunization, mostly
in remote areas where they lack information," Nadirin told Reuters.
Another key factor is Indonesia's years of experience which have left more
than 80 percent of its children already immunized. Support from
international agencies, especially the U.N.'s World Health Organization and
UNICEF, was also crucial.
"No hesitation"
John Budd of the UN children agency told Reuters that Indonesia was quick
in setting up a reporting mechanism for cases of paralysis, which enabled
them to target other areas at risk.
"There was no hesitation. It was a very aggressive approach," he said.
"Nothing more could be done. You can't do any more than they have announced
very early on what they are going to do."
Asked about the patient moved to the capital, Nadirin said her parents had
the right to find medical care where they could but that future suspected
cases should be referred to hospitals in the Sukabumi area.
Indonesia is the 16th country previously believed to be polio-free to be
re-infected in the past 2 years.
The top WHO representative in Indonesia, Georg Petersen, said Jakarta had
plenty of experience with polio vaccination programs and that officials
"have done exactly what they are supposed to do."
The WHO has said the Indonesian cases are almost identical to a strain
circulating in parts of Africa and that the disease may have reached the
country from Africa via the Middle East.
Health officials said it may have been carried by a migrant worker or a Haj
pilgrim who visited Saudi Arabia before returning to Indonesia, the world's
most populous Muslim nation.
[Byline: Achmad Sukarsono]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The number of confirmed cases of paralytic polio are increasing in this
current outbreak, not surprising as there were pending suspected cases at
the time of the 1st announcement (see prior ProMED-mail postings). The
additional information on the identification of 14 "positive contact cases"
is also not surprising, as this is an area where immunization coverage with
polio vaccine was identified to be low, and therefore, there was a
significant susceptible population. As discussed in earlier postings on
polio, the range of paralytic to non-paralytic infections observed during
outbreaks has been between one in 50 to one in 1000, with an average cited
as one in 200 (for each case of paralytic polio, there are between 50 and
1000, with an average of 200, others infected with poliovirus, but, who do
not develop paralytic disease). Hence, one would expect to find "positive
contact cases" in the general area as an indication of current circulation
of the wild poliovirus. As to whether there has been further circulation of
the wild poliovirus to other geographic areas on Java or other islands in
the Indonesian archipelago, only time and good surveillance for AFP will
tell. - Mod.MPP]
